hode Island]], [[United States|U.S.]]}}\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education    = [[Brown University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Georgetown University]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n|website      = {{url|cicilline.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''David Nicola Cicilline''' ({{IPAc-en|s|\u026a|s|\u0268|\u02c8|l|i\u02d0|n|i}}; born July 15, 1961) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|RI|1}} since 2011.<ref name=\"Cotter\">{{cite news\n |url=http://newsblog.projo.com/2010/11/congressional-district-1-races.html \n |title=Congressional District 1 race's final tally \n |accessdate=2010-11-02 \n |last=Cotter \n |first=Pamela \n |date=November 2, 2010 \n |publisher=Providence Journal \n |deadurl=yes \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101108092952/http://newsblog.projo.com:80/2010/11/congressional-district-1-races.html \n |archivedate=2010-11-08 \n |df= \n}}</ref> He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. He previously served as [[List of mayors of Providence, Rhode Island|Mayor of Providence]], [[Rhode Island]] from 2003 to 2011, and was [[List of the first LGBT holders of political offices in the United States|the first openly gay]] mayor of a U.S. state capital.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-95916251/leading-providence-david-cicilline-becomes-the-first |title = Leading Providence: David Cicilline becomes the first openly gay mayor of a U.S. state capital |accessdate = 2007-06-29 |last = Dahir |first = Mubarak  |date = December 24, 2002 |publisher = The Advocate }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Berg|first=Linda|title=Jewish Congressional Candidate Profile: Mayor David Cicilline|url=http://www.njdc.org/blog/post/profilemayordavidcicilline050710#|publisher=National Jewish Democratic Council|accessdate=6 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and law career==\nCicilline was born July 15, 1961, in Providence, Rhode Island. His mother, Sabra (n\u00e9e Peskin), is [[Jews|Jewish]], and his father, John Francis \"Jack\" Cicilline, is [[Italian American]] and Catholic.<ref name=\"brownalumnimagazine.com\">\n{{cite journal\n|url= http://www.brownalumnimagazine.com/content/view/1151/40/\n|title= On the Campaign Trail\n|first= Zachary\n|last= Block\n|journal= Brown Alumni Magazine\n|publisher= Brown University\n|date= September\u2013October 2002\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/David-N-Cicilline/9514417573 |title=Niet compatibele browser |publisher=Facebook |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref><ref>[http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-870980/Leading-Providence-David-Cicilline-becomes.html]</ref> His father is a prominent attorney in Providence who defended local [[American Mafia|Mafia]] figures in the 1970s and 1980s and was an aide to Mayor [[Joseph A. Doorley Jr.]].<ref name=\"BAM\">{{cite journal|last1=Block|first1=Zachary|title=On the Campaign Trail|date=October 2002|url=http://www.brownalumnimagazine.com/content/view/1151/40/|accessdate=22 November 2016|publisher=Brown University|location=Providence|quote=His father, Jack ... is an attorney well known for defending local organized-crime figures.}}</ref>\n\nHe was raised in Providence before moving to [[Narragansett, Rhode Island|Narragansett]]. In high school, he served as president of his graduating class and participated in the [[Close Up Foundation|Close Up Washington]] civic education program before heading to [[Brown University]], where he established a branch of the [[College Democrats]] with his classmate, [[John F. Kennedy Jr|John F. Kennedy, Jr]]. He took a degree in political science, graduating [[magna cum laude]] in 1983. He then went to [[Georgetown University Law Center]] where he earned a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]]\n\nHe remained in [[Washington, D.C.]], for a while to work as a lawyer and [[Public defender|Public Defender Service]].\n\n==Rhode Island House of Representatives (1995\u20132003)==\n\n===Elections===\nHe ran for the [[Rhode Island Senate]] in 1992 against incumbent senator [[Rhoda Perry]] but lost the Democratic primary. Two years later, he was elected to the [[Rhode Island House of Representatives]], representing the 4th district on Providence's East Side. He won the Democratic primary to succeed retiring Rep. Linda J. Kushner with 56% of the vote and was unopposed in the general election.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/projo/access/575898981.html?dids=575898981:575898981&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+14%2C+1994&author=&pub=The+Providence+Journal&desc=House+races+go+to+incumbents+Anderson%2C+San+Bento+returned+to+office+*David+N.+Cicilline+wins+primary+for+Rep.+Linda+J.+Kushner's+seat.&pqatl=google|title=House races go to incumbents Anderson, San Bento returned to office *David N. Cicilline wins primary for Rep. Linda J. Kushner's seat|date=Sep 14, 1994|work=[[The Providence Journal]]}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nAccording to his website, he \"earned a reputation as a fierce champion of political reform and gun safety, and his dedication to ethics won him Common Cause\u2019s top ranking.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cicilline.house.gov/about-me/full-biography |title=Full Biography &#124; Congressman David Cicilline |publisher=Cicilline.house.gov |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n\n==Mayor of Providence (2003\u20132011)==\n\n===Elections===\nCicilline was elected in a landslide in November 2002 with 84% of the vote, following the downfall of controversial mayor [[Vincent Cianci]] and the aftermath of [[Operation Plunder Dome]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-26978840_ITM |title=Article: Leading Providence: David Cicilline becomes the first openly gay mayor of... &#124; AccessMyLibrary \u2013 Promoting library advocacy |publisher=AccessMyLibrary |date=2002-12-24 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> He succeeded acting mayor John J. Lombardi, who served out Cianci's term and decided not to run in the following election.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url= http://www.projo.com/digitalbulletin/content/projo-2002-cicilline.65a4c79.html\n|accessdate= 2009-04-03\n|title= Mayor-elect Cicilline announces transition plans\n|date= 2002-11-14\n|first= Jack\n|last= Perry\n|publisher= [[Providence Journal]]\n}}</ref> In 2006, Cicilline won an easy re-election with 83 percent of the vote.<ref name=prov>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceri.com/government/mayor.php |title=City of Providence \u2013 Mayor David N. Cicilline |publisher=Providenceri.com |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> A Brown University survey in September 2007 found that 64 percent of state residents approved of the job Cicilline was doing in Providence. By February 2008, that number had dropped to 51 percent. And in September 2008, his popularity fell to 46 percent.<ref>{{cite news|author=Marcelo, Philip |title='Providence Mayor Cicilline's approval rating sinks' |url=http://politicsblog.projo.com/2009/02/providence-mayo-1.html |work=Providence Journal |date=2009-02-19 |accessdate=2009-07-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715122149/http://politicsblog.projo.com/2009/02/providence-mayo-1.html |archivedate=2011-07-15 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Accomplishments===\nProvidence has experienced a significant drop in crime, attributed by some to [[community policing]]. As of 2007, Providence saw its lowest crime rate in 30 years.  The city has eliminated 14 percent of management positions, dropped to 17th in the state for per-capita tax and received an \"A\" bond rating from all three major bond-rating agencies.<ref name=\"prov\"/>\n\n===Affiliations===\nCicilline was 2008 President of the [[National Conference of Democratic Mayors]]. As mayor, he was a member of the [[Mayors Against Illegal Guns Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.mayorsagainstillegalguns.org/html/about/members.shtm\n|title= Coalition Members\n|publisher= Mayors Against Illegal Guns\n|accessdate= 2007-09-21\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070912095606/http://www.mayorsagainstillegalguns.org/html/about/members.shtml <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-09-12}}</ref> a [[bi-partisan]] group with the stated goal of \"making the public safer by getting illegal guns off the streets.\" The Coalition was co-chaired by [[Boston]] Mayor [[Thomas Menino]] and [[New York City]] Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]].\n\nIn 2009, Cicilline served as one of six selection committee members for the [[Rudy Bruner Award for Urban Excellence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brunerfoundation.org/rba/index.php?page=committees&sidebar=1 |title=Rudy Bruner Award for Urban Excellence |publisher=Brunerfoundation.org |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>\n\n===Mayoral policies===\nCicilline's administration focused on the residential neighborhoods of Providence, as well as the \"Renaissance\" areas of downtown and [[Federal Hill, Providence, Rhode Island|Federal Hill]] that thrived under Cianci, and continued the promotion of the city via the tax breaks given to artists and movie productions. A former state legislator, he overcame the animosity between state and city government that had existed under Cianci.\n\nIn May 2009, Cicilline gained national headlines after proposing a $150 per semester Head Tax on each of the 25,000 college students attending four universities in the city. The tax was an effort to close $6 to $8 million of a reported $17 million city budget shortfall.  The Associated Press reported that if enacted, it would become the first-in-the-nation tax on students simply for being enrolled and attending college within the city limits.<ref>[http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090513/ap_on_re_us/us_taxing_college_students ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521001000/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090513/ap_on_re_us/us_taxing_college_students |date=May 21, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nCicilline has expressed concern about the [[Providence metropolitan area]]'s [[carbon footprint]]. As mayor, he sought to implement a [[streetcar]]/[[light rail]]-type system for the city. He also focused efforts to fight poverty. He won passage of a vacant-and-abandoned property penalty, to provide an economic disincentive for banks to keep properties off the housing market for extended periods of time. He also proposed municipal bonds for the purpose of buying foreclosed properties to expand housing.<ref>{{cite web|author=\u201c\u201d |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pLBl3XaQBgs&feature=user |title=YouTube \u2013 Mayor David Cicilline of Providence, Rhode Island |publisher=Hk.youtube.com |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>\n\nCicilline is a strong proponent of [[after-school activity|after-school activities]] as a means of improving opportunities for children.<ref name=\"governing.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.governing.com/articles/mayors-dc.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-10-31 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006081034/http://governing.com/articles/mayors-dc.htm |archivedate=2008-10-06 |df= }}</ref> As mayor, Cicilline served as Chair of the Standing Committee for Children, Health and Human Services of the [[United States Conference of Mayors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmayors.org/usmayornewspaper/documents/03_22_10/pg15_about_mayor.asp |title=The U.S. Conference of Mayors : Children, Health & Human Services |publisher=Usmayors.org |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> He has also been recognized for his efforts to establish youth programming and to strengthen ties among  schools, businesses and local government, in order to expand access to after-school programming. Under Cicilline, city officials worked with Rhode Island\u2019s Education Partnership to form PASA, the Providence After School Alliance.<ref name=\"governing.com\"/> Cicilline also serves on the board of the national nonprofit [[Afterschool Alliance]], an organization that works to promote and to support after-school activities for all children.<ref>http://www.afterschoolalliance.org/press_archives/Cicilline_111405.pdf</ref>\n\nBetween 1980 and 2009, most prostitution was legal in Rhode Island.<ref name=\"Arditi\">{{cite news |author=Arditi, Lynn |title='Behind Closed Doors\" How RI Decriminalized Prostitution |url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/PROSTITUTION_LAW31_05-31-09_NVEHGBH_v161.3e90048.html |work=Providence Journal |date=2009-05-31 |accessdate=2009-07-03}}</ref> As mayor, Cicilline was a strong advocate for outlawing it.<ref name=\"Press Release From Mayors Office\">{{cite news |author=Press Release From Mayors Office |title=MAYOR CICILLINE URGES RI SENATE TO PASS PROSTITUTION LEGISLATION |url=http://www.providenceri.com/press/article.php?id=515 |work=Office of The Mayor |date=2009-05-31 |accessdate=2009-07-11}}</ref> Cicilline personally testified in Superior Court to stop the opening of \"spas\" in Providence, and discussed his position in the 2009 documentary ''[[Happy Endings?]]''.<ref name=\"Press Release From Mayors Office\"/><ref>{{cite news |author=Arditi, Lynn |title=Film Chronicles RI's Asian Brothels |url=http://www.projo.com/art/content/HAPPY_ENDINGS_FILM_05-24-09_Q9EFHNF_v25.1ecfa95.html |work=Providence Journal |date=2009-05-24 |accessdate=2009-07-03}}</ref>\n<ref>http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1455623/</ref> He lobbied for a prostitution law not only to arrest sex workers and their customers, but also to fine landlords that permitted prostitution on their premises.<ref>{{cite news |author=Cicilline, David |title=Time to End Prostitution in RI |url=http://www.projo.com/opinion/contributors/content/CT_cicilline19_05-19-09_0UE8N0M_v10.4079d22.html |work=Office of The Mayor |date=2009-05-19 |accessdate=2009-07-11}}</ref> On September 2, 2009, Cicilline submitted an ordinance to the City Council to ban indoor prostitution in the city, imposing a $500 fine and a potential 30-day prison sentence on violators.<ref>{{cite news |author=Marcelp, Philip | title=Providence to consider ordinance banning prostitution |url=http://www.projo.com/ri/providence/content/PROVIDENCE_PROSTITUTION_ORDINANC_09-02-09_AKF_v25.36178f1.html |date=2009-09-02}}</ref> On November 3, 2009, Rhode Island Governor [[Donald Carcieri]] signed into law a bill making the buying and selling of sexual services a crime.<ref name=\"Arditi\" /> (''See also: [[Prostitution in Rhode Island]]'')\n\nDuring the 2008 Democratic primaries, Cicilline supported [[Hillary Clinton]]. In August 2008, he attended the [[Democratic National Convention]] in [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]]. While there, he told an interviewer that he now supported [[Barack Obama]], saying \"[t]here is a real sense of hope and optimism about what we're about to do and about a chance in leadership in this country\".<ref>[http://www.wpri.com/Global/story.asp?S=8901866&nav=F2DO ]{{dead link|date=May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===ICE controversy with Governor Carcieri===\nOn June 8, 2008, Marco Riz, an illegal immigrant from [[Guatemala]] who had been arrested twice the previous year while under a deportation order, was charged with the robbery and rape of a 30-year-old woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/kidnap_rape_06-14-08_MRAGURH_v41.373621f.html |title=Suspect charged in Warwick robbery, rape &#124; Rhode Island news &#124; projo.com &#124; The Providence Journal |publisher=projo.com |date=2008-06-14 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> A federal [[Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE) agent criticized the Providence Police Department for not checking Riz's immigration status at the time of his previous arrest.<ref name=\"projo.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/news/stategovernment/content/carcieri_cicilline_immigration_06-26-08_F9ALH_v30.403b5e0.html |title=Case of illegal immigrant fires political feud &#124; State Government &#124; projo.com &#124; The Providence Journal |publisher=projo.com |date=2008-06-26 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> The governor of Rhode Island, [[Donald Carcieri]], blamed Cicilline for the department's failure.  Previously, Carcieri had signed an executive order requiring all state officials to work with ICE on arrests or hirings of illegal immigrants.  When Carcieri asked the same of local agents, Providence Police Chief [[Dean Esserman]] refused.  Cicilline responded that it has been the policy of the Police Department to work with ICE and its database on all arrests, that the policy had been followed when Riz was arrested, and that the ICE had failed to act.<ref name=\"projo.com\"/>\n\nOn July 8, 2008, Rhode Island Governor Donald Carcieri claimed that Cicilline was not upholding his oath of office by failing to report illegal immigrants, suggesting the [[U.S. Attorney]] investigate the mayor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firesociety.com/forum/thread/27362/Gov.-Carcieri-deepens-war-of-words-with-Providence-Mayor-David-Cicilline/ |title=HugeDomains.com - FireSociety.com is for sale |publisher=Fire Society |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref> Mayor Cicilline responded by accusing Carcieri of \"playing politics\", eight days later writing an op-ed in the [[The Providence Journal|''Providence Journal'']] stating that the city always has and will continue to report all arrests to immigration authorities, and that the focus is therefore inappropriate.<ref>{{cite web|author=David N. Cicilline |url=http://www.projo.com/opinion/columnists/content/CT_cic16_07-16-08_D1AQEET_v28.4118958.html |title=David N. Cicilline: Stop pointing fingers at illegals &#124; Columnists &#124; projo.com &#124; The Providence Journal |publisher=projo.com |date=2008-07-16 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>  Carcieri was term-limited and prevented from running for a third term in 2010.\n\n===Firefighters' union contract arbitration===\n<!--ATTENTION editors: Out of concern that this section may place undue weight (WP:UNDUE) on the issue and acqure a bias, it is asked that any edits to this section be discussed on the talk page [[Talk:David Cicilline]] and agreed upon before changing.  Thanks!---->Beginning in 2003, Cicilline was engaged in a dispute with the Providence Firefighters labor union, Local 799. In a July 2002 email Cicilline sent to the members of Local 799, he indicated that he hoped to resolve their pending contract dispute with the city within 30 days of taking office. In August, Cicilline said in an interview that it was impossible for him to promise to bring the contract negotiations to a successful conclusion owing to the unpredictability of his negotiating partners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.www.browndailyherald.com/media/storage/paper472/news/2005/10/04/Metro/Providence.Firefighters.Still.Without.Contract.Increase.Assistance.To.Brown.Ems-1008109.shtml |title=The Brown Daily Herald \u2013 Providence firefighters, still without contract, increase assistance to Brown EMS |publisher=Media.www.browndailyherald.com |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The city and the union had been in arbitration in every contract year since 2002, with Cicilline appealing one arbitration decision to the Rhode Island Supreme Court. The appeal was rejected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/ri/providence/content/MC_ARBITRATION_04-08-08_FE9M7Q2_v11.32f3e81.html |title=City appeal of firefighter arbitration rejected by court &#124; Providence &#124; projo.com &#124; The Providence Journal |publisher=projo.com |date=2008-04-08 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Democratic vice presidential nominee John Edwards canceled a fundraising appearance in Providence in support of the Local 799.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/extra/election/content/projo-20040927-edwards.15ae1f17.html |title=Extra: Election &#124; projo.com &#124; The Providence Journal |publisher=projo.com |date=2004-09-27 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>  In 2007, [[Hillary Clinton]] asked Cicilline, a Clinton supporter, not to attend a Clinton rally because of threats by the union to picket the appearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/CICILLINE_BARRED_02-22-08_FS93UHE_v8.38dfb05.html|title=Clinton campaign tells Cicilline to stay away when she\u2019s in R.I. &#124; Rhode Island news &#124; projo.com &#124; The Providence Journal|publisher=projo.com|date=2008-02-22|accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/projo_09192007_pickets.eda03b6c.html|title=In the face of pickets, Cicilline resign from Clinton's R.I. campaign|publisher=projo.com|date=2007-09-19 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>\n\nBoth the Rhode Island AFL-CIO and the International Association of Fire Fighters (IAFF) censured Cicilline for his conduct in this matter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iaff.org/Comm/SpotLight/06Stories/100506ProvidenceCensure.htm |title=Local Scene |publisher=IAFF |accessdate=2010-07-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727160027/http://www.iaff.org/Comm/SpotLight/06Stories/100506ProvidenceCensure.htm |archivedate=2011-07-27 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/ri/providence/content/MC_CENSURE_09-18-08_GCBKINR_v14.1a5434c.html|title=Mayor lands censure over firefighter contracts|publisher=projo.com|date=2008-09-18|accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> In 2009, due to the union picketline, the Obama administration canceled [[Joe Biden]]'s appearance at the U.S. Conference of Mayors in Providence in the interests of remaining neutral in the conflict.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/cityhall/1615292,CST-NWS-picket10.article |title=Daley, Obama at odds over meeting's picket line|publisher=Suntimes.com|date=2009-06-10|accessdate=2010-07-12|first=Fran|last=Spielman}}</ref>\n\n===Tax office controversy===\nIn June 2008, John M. Cicilline, brother of Mayor Cicilline, pleaded guilty to conspiracy, obstruction of justice and making false statements for his role in the courthouse corruption scheme. Federal prosecutors indicted John Cicilline, disbarred attorney Joseph Bevilacqua, Jr., and two assistants in January 2007.  According to court documents, the two attorneys spun a complicated scheme to win leniency in a drug trafficking case.<ref>{{cite news |author=Russ, Hilary |title=Brother of Providence, RI, Mayor Headed to Prison |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=5844687 |agency=Associated Press |date=2008-09-19 |accessdate=2009-07-11}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nBefore reporting to prison, John M. Cicilline gave the city of Providence a $75,000 check for taxes owed by a client, but asked that the check not be cashed and only held as collateral.  Two of the mayor\u2019s top aides told the city tax collector Robert Ceprano, not to cash the check because it would bounce. In four instances, Ceprano said mayoral aides pressured him to perform tax favors for the mayor\u2019s friends and/or campaign contributors. The mayor claimed the taxpayers had been given relief because  the city had made errors on their taxes\u2014not because they were his friends or contributors. During the controversy, Ceprano was fired <ref>{{cite news |author= Stanton, Mike |title=Providence tax collector says he was pressured to give favors |url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/Cicilline_Audit_01-24-09_HED2RHS_v18.3fec501.html |work=Providence Journal |date=2008-01-24 |accessdate=2009-07-11}}</ref>\n\nOn May 10, 2009, Robert Ceprano filed a lawsuit against the City of Providence alleging conspiracy, corruption, libel and wrongful termination. The suit accuses John M. Cicilline, the mayor\u2019s imprisoned brother, of attempting to defraud the City of Providence by writing a bad check for $75,000 on behalf of a delinquent taxpayer. Furthermore, it alleges, the mayor and his aides \u201cwillfully conspired...to conceal John Cicilline\u2019s illegal activities\u201d. Ceprano also charges that he was fired not for poor job performance, but because he resisted the mayor\u2019s efforts to perform tax favors for political friends and supporters.  Lawyers for Ceprano are asking for $10 million.<ref>{{cite news |author= Stanton, Mike |title=Fired Providence tax collecter alleges corruption |url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/Ceprano_Lawsuit_05-13-09_O6EBP9J_v13.3b512a6.html |work=Providence Journal |date=2008-05-13 |accessdate=2009-07-11}}</ref> The single count complaint against John Cicilline was dismissed by Judge Kristin Rodgers on November 17, 2009.<ref>Court Docket 09-2712</ref>\n\n===Budget controversy===\nShortly after assuming office, Cicilline's successor as the Mayor of the City of Providence, Angel Taveras, announced that the City was facing a \"category 5\" hurricane due to its substantial debt. Tavares was compelled to engage in austerity cuts including teacher layoffs and paycuts for city employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.browndailyherald.com/mobile/city-looks-to-renegotiate-tax-agreement-with-the-university-1.2505142 |work=Brown Daily Herald\n|author= Peracchio, Claire  |title=City looks to renegotiate tax agreement with the University}}\n</ref> The total structural debt inherited by Tavares in 2011 was $180 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/rhode-island/statements/2011/mar/20/david-cicilline/cicilline-says-providence-had-very-little-reserve-/|title = Cicilline says Providence had \"very little\" in reserve fund when he took office}}</ref>\n\nA report commissioned by the City of Providence found that the Cicilline administration had transferred funds from the Undesignated Surplus (the city's cash reserves) without the proper approval of the City Council, had not provided financial information on a timely basis to the independent auditor, the City Council or the Internal Auditor, and had not provided the City Council with monthly financial statements or with projections of year-end surpluses or deficits, among other findings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://council.providenceri.com/webfm_send/60 |title = Corrective Action Plan to Restore Sound Financial Management|author1=Matthew M. Clarkin, Jr |author2=Gary Sasse }}</ref> Providence City Council Finance Chairman John Igliozzi accused him of \"hiding the scope of the city\u2019s fiscal woes through 'illusory revenues, borrowing and other tricks.'\"<ref name=\"Under Fire\">{{cite news|title=Rhode Island's David Cicilline under fire|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0311/52081.html|newspaper=Politico}}</ref>\n\nFitch Ratings also downgraded Providence's ratings, citing \"imprudent budgeting decisions and failure to implement recurring budget solutions\". Ciciline, who portrayed himself as a reformer looking to restore transparency to city hall, was criticized by his opponents from the primary and House elections: Democrat Anthony Gemma said that he felt Cicilline had lied his way to federal office and Republican John Loughlin said \u201cYou just don\u2019t lie to people in such a transparent way.\"<ref name=\"Under Fire\"/>\n\nA year later, it was reported that Providence could be on the brink of bankruptcy. Former Mayor Vincent Cianci put much blame on Cicilline for Providence's problems, saying that although he didn't think it was entirely his fault, he did hide it from the public. Experts have said that the only way out for Providence may be to declare bankruptcy.<ref name=\"Hiding Debt\">{{cite news|title=\u2018Buddy\u2019 Cianci takes shots at David Cicilline for \u2018hiding\u2019 $100M debt|url=http://bostonherald.com/news/regional/view/20220330mano_a_mayor_in_providence_cianci_takes_shots_at_cicilline_for_hiding_100m_debt|newspaper=The Boston Herald|date=30 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=Unavoidable>{{cite news|title=Providence Bankruptcy Seen as Unavoidable on Budget Gap|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-03-27/providence-bankruptcy-seen-as-unavoidable-on-budget-gap.html|newspaper=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (2011\u2013Present)==\n\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Rhode Island, 2010#District 1}}\nOn February 13, 2010, Cicilline announced his candidacy for the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] following the retirement of [[Patrick J. Kennedy]]. He won the Democratic primary in September with 37% of the vote: defeating businessman Anthony Gemma (23%), State Representative [[David Segal (politician)|David Segal]] (20%), and state party chairman Bill Lynch (20%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=625417 |title=RI - District 01 - D Primary Race - Sep 14, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://content.usatoday.com/communities/onpolitics/post/2010/09/gay-mayor-wins-dem-nod-for-kennedy-house-seat/1|title = Gay mayor wins Dem nod for Kennedy House seat|author = Kathy Kiely|publisher = USA Today|date = 9/14/2010 at 10:14 PM}}</ref>\n\nIn November, he defeated Republican State Representative [[John J. Loughlin, Jr.|John Loughlin]] with 51% of the vote.<ref name=\"Cotter\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=511270 |title=RI - District 01 Race - Nov 02, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Rhode Island, 2012#District 1}}\nHe ran for re-election in the newly redrawn 1st district, and won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/NewsDetail.html?NewsID=80414 |title=News - R.I. Rep. Cicilline says he will stay in the race for reelection - Apr 11, 2012 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date=2012-04-11 |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>\n\nA February 2012 survey showed Cicilline's approval rating had dropped almost 10% in 3 months, with the percent rating his performance \"excellent or good\" dropping by 24%. Anthony Gemma, Cicilline's primary opponent, said that the poll clearly showed that \"a majority of Rhode Islanders wanted to see Cicilline go.\"<ref name=\"Want out\">{{cite news|title=Gemma says Brown poll shows Rhode Islanders want Cicilline out|url=http://news.providencejournal.com/breaking-news/2012/02/gemma-says-brow.html|newspaper=Providence Journal|date=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 it was reported that although Rhode Island had experienced a population shift of only 7,200, a new congressional map would put 125,000 Rhode Islanders into new districts, which would help Democrats, and notably Cicilline.<ref name=\"Bolstering Cicilline\">{{cite news|title=125K voters moved, bolstering Cicilline |url=http://www.wpri.com/dpp/news/politics/125k-voters-moved-bolstering-cicilline |newspaper=WPRI |date=13 December 2011 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Fellow House Democrat [[Jim Langevin]] accused Cicilline of trying to use the redistricting to aid with his reelection campaign. Possible Republican contenders suggested that it was an attempt to save Cicilline after his approval numbers had dropped. Cicilline commented, saying that he did not attempt to influence the redistricting.<ref name=\"Accuses redistricting\">{{cite news|title=Langevin accuses Cicilline of manipulating congressional redistricting|url=http://news.providencejournal.com/breaking-news/2011/12/cicilline-accus.html|newspaper=Providence Journal|date=13 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Rhode Island, 2014#District 1}}\nHe won re-election to a third term in office.\n\n;2016\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Rhode Island, 2016#District 1}}\nCicilline won re-election to a fourth term in office in the 2016 election. He defeated his opponent, Republican H. Russell Taub, with 64% of the vote.<ref>[http://www.ri.gov/election/results/2016/general_election/races/302.html Rhode Island Board of Elections, Retrieved 2016-11-11.]</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nUpon being sworn in, Cicilline became the fourth openly gay member of Congress.<ref name=\"4th Member\">{{cite news|title=David Cicilline, 4th Openly Gay Member Of Congress, Elected In Rhode Island|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/11/03/david-cicilline-4th-openl_n_778092.html|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=3 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nCicilline says that his biggest priority in Congress is helping the creation of good-paying jobs in Rhode Island. He also has indicated his support for small businesses, seniors, Medicare, and for bringing the troops home.<ref name=\"House Bio\">{{cite web|title=House Biography|url=http://cicilline.house.gov/about-me/full-biography|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives}}</ref>\n\nCicilline has voted with his party 96% of the time.<ref name=\"Votes Database\">{{cite web|title=Cicilline Votes Database|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/members/C001084|work=Congress Votes Database|publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref> He has been described as a \"Populist-Leaning Liberal\".<ref name=Issues2000>{{cite web|title=Issues2000 Profile|url=http://www.issues2000.org/House/David_Cicilline.htm|publisher=Issues2000}}</ref>\n\nAn avid supporter of non-violence, Cicilline has taken a stance against the [[2011 military intervention in Libya|U.S. military presence in Libya]], voting to limit the use of funds supporting [[NATO]] operations in Libya and to remove armed forces from Libya.<ref name=\"votesmart.org\">http://www.votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/7349/david-cicilline Project Vote Smart: Key Votes. Retrieved 2011-19-11.</ref> On a domestic level, he is a strong anti-gun advocate. (He was a founding member of the bipartisan coalition [[Mayors Against Illegal Guns]].)<ref>[http://www.mayorsagainstillegalguns.org/html/members/members.shtml Retrieved 2011-19-11.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020183627/http://www.mayorsagainstillegalguns.org/html/members/members.shtml |date=October 20, 2013 }}</ref> In 2010, the [[Brady Campaign|Brady Campaign to Prevent Gun Violence]] endorsed Cicilline; in 2000, the [[National Rifle Association]] awarded him an F- lifetime score.<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/7349/david-cicilline Project Vote Smart: Interest Group Ratings. Retrieved 2011-19-11.]</ref> Cicilline has also indicated his support for a ban on the sale or transfer of all forms of semi-automatic weapons, for more stringent state restrictions on the purchase and possession of firearms, and for a requirement that manufacturers equip firearms with child-safety locks.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://www.votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/7349/david-cicilline/ Project Vote Smart: Political Courage Test. Retrieved 2011-19-11.</ref> On November 16, 2011, Cicilline made a powerful public statement against the National Right-to-Carry Reciprocity Act which would \u201crequire all states to allow out-of-state visitors to carry concealed firearms as long as the laws of the visitors' home states allow them to do so.\u201d<ref>[http://www.opencongress.org/bill/112-h822/show OpenCongress: H.R. 822. Retrieved 2011-19-11.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521032949/http://www.opencongress.org/bill/112-h822/show |date=May 21, 2011 }}</ref> He insisted that the Second Amendment had nothing to do with this bill, which, he said, would infringe upon the right of state governments to protect the safety of their citizens, and would force communities to accept concealed-carry standards set by other states.<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/public-statement/651917/national-right-to-carry-reciprocity-act-of-2011 Project Vote Smart: David Cicilline\u2019s public statement against the National Right to Carry Reciprocity Act of 2011. Retrieved 2011-19-11.]</ref>\n\nCicilline is [[Support for the legalization of abortion|pro-choice]], and advocates that abortions should always be legally available and that government funding should be provided to clinics and medical facilities that provide abortion services.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> He opposed the Protect Life Act of October 2011, which would ban the use of federal funds to cover any costs under health care plans that pay for abortions and would allow federally funded hospitals to refuse to perform the abortions (even in cases in which the mother's life is in danger).<ref>Basset, Laura (October 13, 2011). http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/11/protect-life-act-anti-abortion-bill_n_1005937.html Huffington Post.</ref> Stating that the bill would put women's lives at risk and would limit \u201chow women can spend their own private dollars to purchase health insurance,\u201d Cicilline declared it \u201coutrageous.\u201d<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/public-statement/644862/protect-life-act Project Vote Smart: David Cicilline\u2019s public statement against the Protect Life Act. Retrieved 2011-19-11.]</ref> He also voted in February 2011 against prohibiting the disbursement of federal funds to [[Planned Parenthood]] and, in May 2011, against prohibiting taxpayer funding of abortion.<ref name=\"votesmart.org\"/> Cicilline has also cosponsored the Violence Against Women Health Initiative Act of 2011 to \u201cimprove the health care system's assessment and response to domestic violence, dating violence, sexual assault, and stalking, and for other purposes.\u201d<ref>[http://www.opencongress.org/bill/112-h1578/show OpenCongress: H.R. 1578. Retrieved 2011-19-11.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309212455/http://www.opencongress.org/bill/112-h1578/show |date=March 9, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nCicilline has declared his support for veterans' \u201caccess to a range of resources in health care, housing, employment, mental health services, and education.\u201d <ref>[http://cicilline.house.gov/issue/veterans Congressman David Cicilline Official Website. Retrieved 2011-19-11.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505092439/http://cicilline.house.gov/issue/veterans |date=May 5, 2011 }}</ref> He has cosponsored the Veterans Dog Training Therapy Act to aid veterans with [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|post-traumatic stress disorder]],<ref>[http://www.opencongress.org/bill/112-h198/show OpenCongress: H.R. 198. Retrieved 2011-19-11.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111104258/http://www.opencongress.org/bill/112-h198/show |date=January 11, 2011 }}</ref> the Disabled Veterans Tax Termination Act to permit disabled veterans to receive both retirement pay and disability compensation,<ref>[http://www.opencongress.org/bill/112-h333/show OpenCongress: H.R. 333. Retrieved 2011-19-11.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515040141/http://www.opencongress.org/bill/112-h333/show |date=May 15, 2011 }}</ref> and the Veteran Employment Transition Act of 2011 to extend work opportunities to recently discharged veterans.<ref>[http://www.opencongress.org/bill/112-h865/show OpenCongress: H.R. 856. Retrieved 2011-19-11.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206230856/http://www.opencongress.org/bill/112-h865/show |date=December 6, 2013 }}</ref> On November 18, 2011, Cicilline said the following about the Vow Hire Heroes Act, which increases job opportunities for veterans: \"This vote ensures that Rhode Island veterans and all of our nation's veterans will receive some of the tools and resources they need to successfully reenter the workforce and provide for their families and loved ones.\u201d<ref>[http://www.vote-smart.org/public-statement/651921/cicilline-praises-house-passage-of-vow-to-hire Project Vote Smart: Cicillene Praises House Passage of Vow to Hire Heroes Act. Retrieved 2011-19-11.]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations|Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations]]\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa|Subcommittee on Middle East and North Africa]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Judiciary|Committee on Judiciary]]'''\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet|Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property, and the Internet]]\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Regulatory Reform, Commercial and Antitrust Law|Subcommittee on Regulatory Reform, Commercial and Antitrust Law]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*Congressional Arts Caucus\n*Congressional Common Ground Caucus (co-founder)\n*[[Congressional Progressive Caucus]]\n*Congressional Buy American Caucus\n*House Manufacturing Caucus\n*Congressional Creative Rights Caucus\n*[[Congressional LGBT Equality Caucus]] (co-chair)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|United States|Rhode Island|LGBT}}\n{{Commons category|David Cicilline}}\n*[http://cicilline.house.gov/ Congressman David Cicilline] official U.S. House site\n*[http://cicilline.com/ David Cicilline for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Rhode_Island/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/David_Cicilline_%5BD-1%5D}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = C001084 | ballot = David_Cicilline | nndb = 478/000167974 | votesmart = 7349 | govtrack = 412470 | opencong = 412470 | rollcall = 7318 | politifact = david-cicilline | fec = H0RI01073 | opensecrets = N00032019 | assets = david-cicilline | legistorm = 2791/Rep_David_Cicilline_RI.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = House/David_Cicilline.htm | congress = david-cicilline/2055 | worldcat = np-cicilline,%20david$1961 | c-span = davidcicilline | imdb = 3078206 | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQA6P5YKP }}\n;Mayor\n*[http://www.citymayors.com/mayors/providence-ma